    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What does % Daily Value mean on a nutrition label?</summary>
        <p>The % Daily Value (%DV) tells you how much one serving of a food contributes to your daily intake of a specific nutrient, based on a 2,000-calorie reference diet. As a general guideline, 5% DV or less is considered low for that nutrient, and 20% DV or more is considered high. Use %DV to quickly compare products and determine whether a food is high or low in specific nutrients you want to consume more of (like fiber) or limit (like sodium).</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between added sugars and total sugars?</summary>
        <p>Total sugars include both naturally occurring sugars (like lactose in milk or fructose in fruit) and added sugars. Added sugars are sugars and syrups that are added during processing or preparation, including table sugar, high-fructose corn syrup, honey, and fruit juice concentrates. The FDA recommends limiting added sugars to less than 10% of daily calories (50 grams on a 2,000-calorie diet). Naturally occurring sugars in whole fruits and plain dairy are generally not a health concern.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How accurate are nutrition labels?</summary>
        <p>The FDA allows a 20% margin of error on nutrition label values. This means a product labeled as 200 calories per serving could legally contain anywhere from 160 to 240 calories. While most major manufacturers are reasonably accurate, smaller brands may have larger discrepancies. For most people, labels are accurate enough for general dietary planning. If you need precise tracking, be aware of this potential variation.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Does "natural" on a food label mean it is healthy?</summary>
        <p>Not necessarily. The FDA does not have a strict regulatory definition for the term "natural" on food labels. Generally, it means the product does not contain artificial flavors, colors, or synthetic substances, but a "natural" product can still be high in sugar, sodium, saturated fat, and calories. Similarly, "organic" refers to farming and production methods, not nutritional quality. Always read the full Nutrition Facts panel rather than relying on front-of-package claims.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why do serving sizes matter so much when reading nutrition labels?</summary>
        <p>All the nutrition information on a label is based on one serving, but many packages contain multiple servings. If a bag of chips lists 150 calories per serving and the bag contains 8 servings, eating the whole bag means consuming 1,200 calories. The updated FDA labels now require a more realistic serving size and dual-column labeling for packages that could reasonably be consumed in one sitting, making it easier to see both per-serving and per-package nutrition information.</p>
      </details>
